[https://twitter.com/HelenBranswell See Helen Branswell tweet for 16 Jun 2020 CMRE report, the high points being the 5 health zones covering a large region. "Complicates the response but may limit spread."
Total of 14 confirmed cases with cumulative number of cases being 17. In total, there are 11 deaths (8 confirmed and 3 probable)
Bikoro: 3 cases confirmed, with 6 deaths (5 days without confirmed cases)
Bolamba: 2 cases confirmed (6 days without confirmed cases)
Iboko: 1 case confirmed (4 days without confirmed cases)
Mbandaka: 6 cases confirmed, of which 4 died and 3 probable cases (13 days without confirmed cases for Ipeko and Maman W'Elikya health areas and 10 days for Libiki)
Wangata: 2 cases confirmed, of which 1 died (13 days without confirmed cases)]

******
[2] Summaries
- Mon 15 Jun 2020. News scan
[CIDRAP (Center for Infectious Disease Research and Policy) abridged, edited]
https://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2020/06/news-scan-jun-15-2020

Officials reported 5 more illnesses and 3 more deaths in a new Ebola outbreak in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC), according to figures reported today [Mon 15 Jun 2020] by the country's multisectoral Ebola response committee (CMRE; see above).

The new developments raise the outbreak total to 17 cases, 14 of them confirmed and 3 listed as probable. The new deaths raise the fatality count to 11.

The World Health Organization (WHO) said last week in its latest situation report that the outbreak has affected 6 health areas in 3 health zones: Mbandaka, Wangata, and Bikoro. Sequencing suggests that it is not related to the larger ongoing outbreak in the eastern part of the country, where the total stands at 3463 cases, 2280 of them fatal. If no new cases are reported by 25 Jun 2020, the larger outbreak will be declared over.

